				\begin{document}$${{{{{{\rm{FE}}}}}}}_{x}( \% )=\frac{{n}_{x}\times {C}_{x}\times u\times F}{I\times {V}_{M}}\times 100 \%$$\end{document}where F is the Faraday constant (96485 C mol−1), I is the total current density, nx is electrons transferred for reduction to product x, Cx is volume fraction of the product x detected by GC, u is outlet gas flowrate and VM is molar volume (22.4 L mol−1).

The formate products were quantified by 1H NMR spectra measured with a Bruker 400 MHz spectrometer. Typically, 400 µL of the electrolyte after CO2RR electrolysis was mixed with 200 µL of D2O containing 50 ppm (m/m) dimethyl sulphoxide (DMSO) as the internal standard. The area ratio of the formate peak to the DMSO peak was compared to the standard curve to quantify the concentration of formate. The molar quantity of formate (nformate) was calculated via multiplying the concentration of formate with the volume of the catholyte. The Faradaic efficiency of the formate (FEformate) can be calculated by the following equation:3FEformate(%)=2×F×nformateI×t×100%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
